PROJECT.NAME: Takifugu rubripes
PROJECT.TITLE: Gill of Takifugu rubripes Transcriptome
PROJECT.DESCRIPTION: The fish gill, as one of the mucosal barriers, plays an important role in mucosal immune response. The fish swimbladder functions for regulating buoyancy. The fish swimbladder has long been postulated as a homologous organ of the tetrapod lung, but the molecular evidence is scarce. In order to provide new information that is complementary to gill immune genes, initiate new research directions concerning the genetic basis of the gill immune response and understand the molecular function of swimbladder as well as its relationship with lungs, transcriptome analysis of the fugu Takifugu rubripes gill and swimbladder was carried out by RNA-Seq.

PROJECT.TITLE: Gonadal Transcriptomes of Tiger Pufferfish (Takifugu rubripes)
PROJECT.DESCRIPTION: In 2012, by extensive genetic mapping and association mapping, Kamiya et al., identified a missense SNP in the Amhr2 gene as a likely candidate for the master sex-determination polymorphism. However, the factors involved in the downstream of gonadal differentiation of such an important fish species have not yet been studied well, we have got only limited message about fugu sex differentiation, and more sex related genes and their functions need to be studied. Further identification of the expression profile of genes involved in gonadal development using RNA-seq may help to illuminate the gene regulatory network controlling sex determination and subsequent maintenance of phenotypic sex.
